Poll-drain the uartlite TX ring so userspace console output works without a
wired UART interrupt.

chiron has no PLIC interrupt *delivery* in the golden model / RTL, so the
IRQ-driven TX path stalls userspace output once the FIFO fills (the polled
kernel-printk path keeps working, which is why early boot is visible but the
shell banner stops mid-line). Drain the whole TX ring in start_tx instead.
ulite_transmit() returns 0 once the FIFO is full or the ring is empty, so this
is safe on real hardware too.

Apply from the linux/ source tree:  patch -p1 < this_file

--- a/drivers/tty/serial/uartlite.c
+++ b/drivers/tty/serial/uartlite.c
@@ -266,7 +266,16 @@ static void ulite_stop_tx(struct uart_port *port)

 static void ulite_start_tx(struct uart_port *port)
 {
-	ulite_transmit(port, uart_in32(ULITE_STATUS, port));
+	/*
+	 * Drain the whole TX ring here instead of sending a single byte and
+	 * waiting for the TX-empty IRQ. On platforms without a wired uartlite
+	 * interrupt (e.g. the chiron golden model / RTL, which has no PLIC
+	 * delivery) the IRQ never fires, so userspace console output would
+	 * otherwise stall after the first byte. ulite_transmit() returns 0 once
+	 * the FIFO is full or the ring is empty, so this is safe on real HW too.
+	 */
+	while (ulite_transmit(port, uart_in32(ULITE_STATUS, port)))
+		;
 }

 static void ulite_stop_rx(struct uart_port *port)
